tion in the United Kingdom#Northern Ireland|2004]]\n| align=center|87,559\n| align=center|15.9%\n| align=center|{{Composition bar|0|3|hex={{Social Democratic and Labour Party/meta/color}}}}\n|-\n| align=center|[[2009 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom#Northern Ireland|2009]]\n| align=center|78,489\n| align=center|16.1%\n| align=center|{{Composition bar|0|3|hex={{Social Democratic and Labour Party/meta/color}}}}\n|-\n| align=center|[[Northern Ireland (European Parliament constituency)#2014|2014]]\n| align=center|81,594\n| align=center|13.0%\n| align=center|{{Composition bar|0|3|hex={{Social Democratic and Labour Party/meta/color}}}}\n|-\n| align=center|[[Northern Ireland (European Parliament constituency)#2019|2019]]\n| align=center|78,589\n| align=center|13.7%\n| align=center|{{Composition bar|0|3|hex={{Social Democratic and Labour Party/meta/color}}}}\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Demography and politics of Northern Ireland]]\n*[[Labour Party in Northern Ireland]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Social Democratic and Labour Party}}\n*{{Official website}}\n{{Social Democratic and Labour Party}}\n{{Navboxes\n|list=\n{{Political parties in Northern Ireland}}\n{{Political parties in the United Kingdom}}\n{{Party of European Socialists}}\n{{2011 United Kingdom Alternative Vote referendum}}}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Social Democratic and Labour Party| ]]\n[[Category:Irish republicanism]]\n[[Category:Social democratic parties]]\n[[Category:1970 establishments in Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:Labour parties in Northern Ireland]]\n", "name_user": "Sbiggs02", "label": "safe", "comment": "added a citation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Social_Democratic_and_Labour_Party"}
{"title_page": "Peter Bridgmont", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Peter Bridgmont\n| image              = File:Peter Bridgmont.jpg\n| image_size         = 320px\n| caption            = Thespian Peter Bridgmont on the set of \u00c1lvaro Ramos' \"The Magic Box\" (2011).\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1929|01|00|df=yes}}\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|2019|06|24|1929|01|01|df=yes}}\n| nationality        = British\n| education          = [[Wynstones School]]\n| alma_mater         = [[Guildhall School of Music & Drama]]\n| occupation         = Actor\n| years_active       = 1950\u2013present\n| spouse             = Barbara Brown (Bridgmont)\n| children           = Andrew Bridgmont\n| website            = https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1782178/\n}}\n'''Peter Bridgmont''' (January 1929 - 24 June 2019)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://goetheanum.co/fr/nouvelles/peter-bridgmont|title=Goetheanum {{!}} Peter Bridgmont, in memoriam|last=team|first=Maxime Le Roux, Nathan Querido, Das Goetheanum Wochenschrift|website=Goetheanum|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> was an English actor, acting professor and author who has had an extensive career on stage, film, and television spanning over 60 years. Bridgmont, who is a [[Guildhall School of Music and Drama]] graduate,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.liberationofacting.com/|title=Chrysalis|date=14 February 2017|website=liberationofacting.com|access-date=21 February 2018}}</ref> was mostly known as one of the former members of the [[Theatre Workshop]] and one of the original cast members of the very first [[West End theatre|West End]] production of [[Agatha Christie]]'s ''[[The Mousetrap]]'' opening in 1952 at the [[Ambassadors Theatre (London)|Ambassadors Theatre]] which went on to become the world's longest running [[Stage productions|stage production]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Mousetrap Man|last=Saunders|first=Peter|publisher=Harper Collins|year=1972|isbn=978-0-00-211538-4|location=London|pages=}}</ref> On screen, he notably appeared in ''[[The Great War (TV series)|The Great War]]'' (1964) narrated by [[Michael Redgrave]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ramsden|first=J. A.|year=2002|title=The Great War: The Making of the Series|journal=Historical Journal of Film, Radio and Television|volume=22 (1): 7\u201319}}</ref> and the [[British television]] drama series ''[[Z-Cars]]'' (1962\u20131978) directed by [[Christopher Morahan]] ([[Order of the British Empire|CBE]], 1929\u20132017).<ref>{{Cite book|title=The British Television Drama Research Guide, 1950\u20131997, with Full Archive Holdings, second revised edition|last=Down and Perry|first=Richard, Christopher|publisher=Kaleidoscope Publishing|year=1997|isbn=|location=Bristol|pages=DZ1\u2013DZ5}}</ref> He founded the Chrysalis Theatre Acting School in London in 1975 and has long taught '[[Voice acting|voice]]' and '[[gesture]]' at the [[Shakespeare's Globe]].\n\n== Early life ==\nBridgmont grew up among actors, singers, dancers and [[clown]]s. His father was a pianist for the [[silent movies]], his mother was a cellist and both also worked for the [[BBC]]. Bridgmont used to attend his parents' [[pantomime]]s as a child including one during which English musical theatre and [[operetta]]s actress [[Jean Colin]] (28 years old at the time; 24 March 1905 \u2013 7 March 1989) ironically promised him that she would marry him. He was educated at the [[Wynstones School]], a [[Steiner Waldorf School|Steiner Waldorf school]] in [[Gloucestershire]], in the [[Cotswolds]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://goetheanum.co/fr/nouvelles/peter-bridgmont|title=Goetheanum {{!}} Peter Bridgmont, in memoriam|last=team|first=Maxime Le Roux, Nathan Querido, Das Goetheanum Wochenschrift|website=Goetheanum|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> Peter went on to compete in order to win a Gold Cup at the [[Cheltenham Festivals]] as he was completing school. Bridgmont came second but the then festival director, Mr Robin arranged for Peter to go to the [[Guildhall School of Music & Drama]] in London, which he did.\n\n== Career ==\nBridgmont starred alongside Baron [[Richard Attenborough]] ([[Commander of the Order of the British Empire|CBE]], 1923\u2013 2014) in the first [[West End theatre|West End]] production of [[Agatha Christie]]'s ''[[The Mousetrap]]'' opening in 1952 at the [[Ambassadors Theatre (London)|Ambassadors Theatre]], which went on to become the world's longest running [[Stage productions|stage production]]. Bridgmont met his wife Barbara Brown (Bridgmont) while they were both former company members at the [[Theatre Workshop]] whose long-serving director was [[Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]]s graduate [[Joan Littlewood]] (1914\u20132002) and fellow members included [[Richard Harris]] (1930\u20132002), [[Nigel Hawthorne]] ([[Commander of the Order of the British Empire|CBE]]; 1929\u20132001), [[George Sewell]] (1924\u20132007), [[David Scase]] (1919\u20132003), [[Victor Spinetti]] (1929\u20132012), [[John Thaw]] ([[Commander of the Order of the British Empire|CBE]], 1942\u20132002), [[Barbara Windsor]] ([[Dame Commander of the Order of the British Empire|DBE]], 1937\u2013), [[Yootha Joyce]] (1927\u20131980), [[Sheila Hancock]] ([[Commander of the Order of the British Empire|CBE]],1933\u2013), [[Dudley Foster]] (1924\u20131973), [[Marjie Lawrence]] (1932\u20132010), [[Stephen Lewis (actor)|Stephen Lewis]] (1926\u20132015), [[Ewan MacColl]] (1915\u20131989), [[Murray Melvin]] (1932\u2013), [[Frank Norman]] (1930\u20131980), [[John Junkin]] (1930\u20132006), [[Roy Kinnear]] (1934\u20131988), [[Diana Coupland]] (1928\u20132006), [[Shelagh Delaney]] (1938\u20132011), [[Glynn Edwards]] (1931\u20132018) and [[Howard Goorney]] (1921\u20132007). Many [[Theatre Workshop]] productions were transferred to theatres in the [[West End theatre|West End]] and some like as ''[[Oh, What a Lovely War!]]'' and ''[[A Taste of Honey]]'', were made into films.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Theatre Royal: 100 Years of Stratford East|last=Coren|first=Michael|publisher=Quartet Books|year=1984|isbn=978-0-7043-2474-9|location=London|pages=|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/theatreroyal100y00core}}</ref> Peter was introduced to and worked with one of the pioneers of [[modern dance]] in Europe, [[Rudolf von Laban]] ([[Hungarian language|Hungarian]]: ''Rezs\u0151 L\u00e1b\u00e1n de V\u00e1raljas''; 1879-1958) through his [[Laban Movement Analysis]], [[Labanotation]] (''Kinetography'') and [[Laban Movement Studies|Laban Movement Study]]. The couple relocated to [[Vence]] ([[Occitan language|Occitan]]: ''Ven\u00e7a'') in the hills of the [[Alpes Maritimes]] [[Departments of France|department]] in the French [[Provence-Alpes-C\u00f4te d'Azur]] [[Regions of France|region]] between [[Nice]] and [[Antibes]], formed their own [[Mime artist|Mime]] Company and collaborated with [[Modernism|modernist]] [[theatre practitioner]], director and [[scenic designer]] [[Edward Gordon Craig]] ([[Companion of Honour|CH]] [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire|OBE]] 1872\u20131966), the son of actress Dame [[Ellen Terry]] ([[Knight Grand Cross of the Order of the British Empire|GBE]], 1847\u20131928). After three years of [[Touring theatre|touring]] they came back to the United Kingdom.\n\n== Chrysalis Theatre Acting School ==\nThe couple studied the formation of the art of [[Voice acting|dramatic speech]] and [[gesture]] created by Austrian philosopher, [[social reformer]], [[Architecture|architect]] and [[Esotericism|esotericist]] [[Rudolf Steiner]] (1861\u20131925). They started the '''Boundaries Theatre Company''' which became their own drama school in 1975, the Chrysalis Theatre Acting School in the same [[London]] building they had bought in [[Balham]]. The theatre' venue had been used by the [[Spiritualist Association of Great Britain]] until then. The students who came from all over the world such as Japan or certain [[African countries]] included [[Spanish citizenship|Spanish]] actress Luz Altamira or Sir [[Mark Rylance]]. The school lasted for thirty years. In the 1990s both of them gave training in [[Voice acting|voice]] and [[gesture]] to the professional company of the [[Shakespeare's Globe]]. Peter also gave courses in both the United States and throughout Europe during the same period.\n\n== La Cris\u00e1lida ==\nBridgmont supported the '''La Cris\u00e1lida Studio''', the first school focused on the 'Art of [[Speech]]' in [[Spain]], founded by his pupils speech artist '''Luz Altamira''' and [[Goya Awards]]-nominated thespian '''\u00c1lvaro Ramos''' as well as actress and author '''Pilar Altamira''' member of the '[[Anthroposophical Society]] of [[Spain]]'. This place also hosted seminars and conferences that Peter Bridgmont regularly offered between 1997 and 2003.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://goetheanum.co/fr/nouvelles/peter-bridgmont|title=Goetheanum {{!}} Peter Bridgmont, in memoriam|last=team|first=Maxime Le Roux, Nathan Querido, Das Goetheanum Wochenschrift|website=Goetheanum|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@portialeigh1/dynamic-spanish-actor-alvaro-ramos-makes-his-mark-across-several-mediums-c2392a7d74d1|title=Dynamic Spanish Actor Alvaro Ramos Makes his Mark Across Several Mediums|last=Leigh|first=Portia|date=2018-01-27|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n== Non-exhaustive bibliography ==\n* ''The Spear Thrower (javelin thrower), a Textbook of Ideas and Exercises for the Actor'' (1983) by Peter Bridgmont ([[ASIN]]: B000O8RJIY)<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Spear Thrower, a Textbook of Ideas and Exercises for the Actor|last=Bridgmont|first=Peter|publisher=An Grianan|year=1983|isbn=|location=London|pages=}}</ref>\n* ''The Liberation of The Actor'' (1992) by Peter Bridgmont ({{ISBN|978-0904693331}}).<ref>{{Cite book|title=Liberation of the Actor|last=Bridgmont|first=Peter|publisher=Temple Lodge Publishing|year=1992|isbn=978-0904693331|location=London|pages=}}</ref>\n\n== Quotes ==\n* English actor, theatre director and playwright [[Mark Rylance|Sir David Mark Rylance Waters]] (born 18 January 1960) who long collaborated with Bridgmont declared:\n<blockquote>''\"Peter and Barbara Bridgmont made a profound difference to my persona as an actor with their teaching about voice and speech. I use the word 'persona' carefully, as they taught me how to move with sound, through sound, persona. In our visual-material age, sound is the great undiscovered or forgotten land for actors and audiences. Reason and Emotion are all very well in speech, much needed, but with Peter and Barbara I learnt of the limbs of speech, the feet, the legs, the arms, the great will and beautiful spirit to move with speech. Just as a marvellous javelin thrower wills his spear down the pitch to the winning distance and harnesses every muscle necessary in perfect balance to achieve his aim, so, when appropriate, we speak in space and silence. It was a lucky day for me when I met them; they know some great secrets and forgotten pathways.\"''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.liberationofacting.com/|title=FOREWORD by Mark Rylance|last=Rylance|first=Mark|date=27 August 2015|website=Liberation of Acting|access-date=11 August 2018}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n* ''\"Readers who are interested in the Art of Drama may also wish to refer to The Liberation of The Actor (1992) by Peter Bridgmont\"''<ref>{{Cite book|title=Rhythms of Learning: What Waldorf Education Offers Children, Parents & Teachers|last=Steiner|first=Rudolf|publisher=SteinerBooks|year=1998|isbn=9780880104517|location=London|pages=}}</ref>\n\n== British Film Institute Archives ==\nA r\u00e9pertoire of Bridgmont's voice work for the year 1966 is available at the [[British Film Institute]] archives as follows:\n* 1966: ''The Sword Must Be Kept Sharp'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]].\n* 1966: ''What Did Greece Matter?'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]] and [[Felix Felton]].\n* 1966: ''It Will Proceed to the End'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]] and [[Felix Felton]].\n* 1966: ''One Perplexity after Another'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]] and [[Felix Felton]].\n* 1966: ''We Are on the Edge of a Precipice'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]] and [[Anton Diffring]].\n* 1966: ''Not a Penny off the Pay'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]] and [[David Bauer (actor)|David Bauer]].\n* 1966: ''It Has Advanced the Footlights'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]] and [[Anton Diffring]].\n* 1966: ''Your Death Knell Has Sounded'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]] and [[Anton Diffring]].\n* 1966: ''War Is Re-enthroned'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]] and [[Anton Diffring]].\n* 1966: ''We Neither Govern Not Misgovern'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]] and [[David Bauer (actor)|David Bauer]].\n* 1966: ''The Popular Masses Are Dull'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]] and [[Anton Diffring]].\n* 1966: ''Germany Is Reawakening'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]] and [[Anton Diffring]].\n* 1966: ''There Lies a Sleeping Giant'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]] and [[Anton Diffring]].\n* 1966: ''Who Can Conquer the Street...'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]] and [[Felix Felton]].\n* 1966: ''On the Idle Hill of Summer'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]] and [[Felix Felton]].\n* 1966: ''Make Room for Peace'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]] and [[Felix Felton]].\n* 1966: ''There Is a Great Tide Turning'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]] and [[Anton Diffring]].\n* 1966: ''This Is Such a Time'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]] and [[David Bauer (actor)|David Bauer]].\n* 1966: ''Boys You Have Been Betrayed'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]] and [[Felix Felton]].\n* 1966: ''Now I Can Die'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]] and [[David Bauer (actor)|David Bauer]].\n* 1966: ''Long Live the War'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]] and [[Felix Felton]].\n* 1966: ''What Hand Would Not Wither'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]], Robert Ayres and [[David Bauer (actor)|David Bauer]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2bc891e6a8|title=Voice work 1966 Bridgmont|date=1 January 2017|website=British Film Institute (BFI)|access-date=11 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Honours ==\n* The documentary on Peter and Barbara directed by [[Spanish citizenship|Spanish]] actor and director \u00c1lvaro Ramos which was eponymously titled '''The Chrysalis''' (2009) won the Best Documentary award at the High Desert International Film Festival in [[Nevada]], United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://clandestinodeactores.com/alvaro-ramos|title=Alvaro's work|date=5 May 2015|website=Clandestino de Actores|access-date=17 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nPeter's son, Andrew Bridgmont, is also an accomplished actor himself who notably starred in [[Matthew Vaughn]]'s ''[[Kingsman: The Secret Service]]'' (2014), [[James Marsh (director)|James Marsh]]'s ''[[The Theory of Everything (2014 film)|The Theory of Everything]]'' (2014) or ''[[Penny Dreadful (TV series)|Penny Dreadful]]'' (2014\u20132016).\n\n== External links ==\n* Bridgmont's [http://www.liberationofacting.com/ official website].\n\n== Sources ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bridgmont, Peter}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:English male dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male Shakespearean actors]]\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:English theatre directors]]\n[[Category:Royal Shakespeare Company members]]\n[[Category:Guildhall School of Music and Drama]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Peter Bridgmont\n| image              = File:Peter Bridgmont.jpg\n| image_size         = 320px\n| caption            = Thespian Peter Bridgmont on the set of \u00c1lvaro Ramos' \"The Magic Box\" (2011).\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1929|df=yes}}\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|2019|06|24|1929|01|01|df=yes}}\n| nationality        = British\n| education          = [[Wynstones School]]\n| alma_mater         = [[Guildhall School of Music & Drama]]\n| occupation         = Actor\n| years_active       = 1950\u2013present\n| spouse             = Barbara Brown (Bridgmont)\n| children           = Andrew Bridgmont\n| website            = https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1782178/\n}}\n'''Peter Bridgmont''' (January 1929 - 24 June 2019)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://goetheanum.co/fr/nouvelles/peter-bridgmont|title=Goetheanum {{!}} Peter Bridgmont, in memoriam|last=team|first=Maxime Le Roux, Nathan Querido, Das Goetheanum Wochenschrift|website=Goetheanum|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> was an English actor, acting professor and author who has had an extensive career on stage, film, and television spanning over 60 years. Bridgmont, who is a [[Guildhall School of Music and Drama]] graduate,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.liberationofacting.com/|title=Chrysalis|date=14 February 2017|website=liberationofacting.com|access-date=21 February 2018}}</ref> was mostly known as one of the former members of the [[Theatre Workshop]] and one of the original cast members of the very first [[West End theatre|West End]] production of [[Agatha Christie]]'s ''[[The Mousetrap]]'' opening in 1952 at the [[Ambassadors Theatre (London)|Ambassadors Theatre]] which went on to become the world's longest running [[Stage productions|stage production]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Mousetrap Man|last=Saunders|first=Peter|publisher=Harper Collins|year=1972|isbn=978-0-00-211538-4|location=London|pages=}}</ref> On screen, he notably appeared in ''[[The Great War (TV series)|The Great War]]'' (1964) narrated by [[Michael Redgrave]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ramsden|first=J. A.|year=2002|title=The Great War: The Making of the Series|journal=Historical Journal of Film, Radio and Television|volume=22 (1): 7\u201319}}</ref> and the [[British television]] drama series ''[[Z-Cars]]'' (1962\u20131978) directed by [[Christopher Morahan]] ([[Order of the British Empire|CBE]], 1929\u20132017).<ref>{{Cite book|title=The British Television Drama Research Guide, 1950\u20131997, with Full Archive Holdings, second revised edition|last=Down and Perry|first=Richard, Christopher|publisher=Kaleidoscope Publishing|year=1997|isbn=|location=Bristol|pages=DZ1\u2013DZ5}}</ref> He founded the Chrysalis Theatre Acting School in London in 1975 and has long taught '[[Voice acting|voice]]' and '[[gesture]]' at the [[Shakespeare's Globe]].\n\n== Early life ==\nBridgmont grew up among actors, singers, dancers and [[clown]]s. His father was a pianist for the [[silent movies]], his mother was a cellist and both also worked for the [[BBC]]. Bridgmont used to attend his parents' [[pantomime]]s as a child including one during which English musical theatre and [[operetta]]s actress [[Jean Colin]] (28 years old at the time; 24 March 1905 \u2013 7 March 1989) ironically promised him that she would marry him. He was educated at the [[Wynstones School]], a [[Steiner Waldorf School|Steiner Waldorf school]] in [[Gloucestershire]], in the [[Cotswolds]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://goetheanum.co/fr/nouvelles/peter-bridgmont|title=Goetheanum {{!}} Peter Bridgmont, in memoriam|last=team|first=Maxime Le Roux, Nathan Querido, Das Goetheanum Wochenschrift|website=Goetheanum|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> Peter went on to compete in order to win a Gold Cup at the [[Cheltenham Festivals]] as he was completing school. Bridgmont came second but the then festival director, Mr Robin arranged for Peter to go to the [[Guildhall School of Music & Drama]] in London, which he did.\n\n== Career ==\nBridgmont starred alongside Baron [[Richard Attenborough]] ([[Commander of the Order of the British Empire|CBE]], 1923\u2013 2014) in the first [[West End theatre|West End]] production of [[Agatha Christie]]'s ''[[The Mousetrap]]'' opening in 1952 at the [[Ambassadors Theatre (London)|Ambassadors Theatre]], which went on to become the world's longest running [[Stage productions|stage production]]. Bridgmont met his wife Barbara Brown (Bridgmont) while they were both former company members at the [[Theatre Workshop]] whose long-serving director was [[Royal Academy of Dramatic Art]]s graduate [[Joan Littlewood]] (1914\u20132002) and fellow members included [[Richard Harris]] (1930\u20132002), [[Nigel Hawthorne]] ([[Commander of the Order of the British Empire|CBE]]; 1929\u20132001), [[George Sewell]] (1924\u20132007), [[David Scase]] (1919\u20132003), [[Victor Spinetti]] (1929\u20132012), [[John Thaw]] ([[Commander of the Order of the British Empire|CBE]], 1942\u20132002), [[Barbara Windsor]] ([[Dame Commander of the Order of the British Empire|DBE]], 1937\u2013), [[Yootha Joyce]] (1927\u20131980), [[Sheila Hancock]] ([[Commander of the Order of the British Empire|CBE]],1933\u2013), [[Dudley Foster]] (1924\u20131973), [[Marjie Lawrence]] (1932\u20132010), [[Stephen Lewis (actor)|Stephen Lewis]] (1926\u20132015), [[Ewan MacColl]] (1915\u20131989), [[Murray Melvin]] (1932\u2013), [[Frank Norman]] (1930\u20131980), [[John Junkin]] (1930\u20132006), [[Roy Kinnear]] (1934\u20131988), [[Diana Coupland]] (1928\u20132006), [[Shelagh Delaney]] (1938\u20132011), [[Glynn Edwards]] (1931\u20132018) and [[Howard Goorney]] (1921\u20132007). Many [[Theatre Workshop]] productions were transferred to theatres in the [[West End theatre|West End]] and some like as ''[[Oh, What a Lovely War!]]'' and ''[[A Taste of Honey]]'', were made into films.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Theatre Royal: 100 Years of Stratford East|last=Coren|first=Michael|publisher=Quartet Books|year=1984|isbn=978-0-7043-2474-9|location=London|pages=|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/theatreroyal100y00core}}</ref> Peter was introduced to and worked with one of the pioneers of [[modern dance]] in Europe, [[Rudolf von Laban]] ([[Hungarian language|Hungarian]]: ''Rezs\u0151 L\u00e1b\u00e1n de V\u00e1raljas''; 1879-1958) through his [[Laban Movement Analysis]], [[Labanotation]] (''Kinetography'') and [[Laban Movement Studies|Laban Movement Study]]. The couple relocated to [[Vence]] ([[Occitan language|Occitan]]: ''Ven\u00e7a'') in the hills of the [[Alpes Maritimes]] [[Departments of France|department]] in the French [[Provence-Alpes-C\u00f4te d'Azur]] [[Regions of France|region]] between [[Nice]] and [[Antibes]], formed their own [[Mime artist|Mime]] Company and collaborated with [[Modernism|modernist]] [[theatre practitioner]], director and [[scenic designer]] [[Edward Gordon Craig]] ([[Companion of Honour|CH]] [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire|OBE]] 1872\u20131966), the son of actress Dame [[Ellen Terry]] ([[Knight Grand Cross of the Order of the British Empire|GBE]], 1847\u20131928). After three years of [[Touring theatre|touring]] they came back to the United Kingdom.\n\n== Chrysalis Theatre Acting School ==\nThe couple studied the formation of the art of [[Voice acting|dramatic speech]] and [[gesture]] created by Austrian philosopher, [[social reformer]], [[Architecture|architect]] and [[Esotericism|esotericist]] [[Rudolf Steiner]] (1861\u20131925). They started the '''Boundaries Theatre Company''' which became their own drama school in 1975, the Chrysalis Theatre Acting School in the same [[London]] building they had bought in [[Balham]]. The theatre' venue had been used by the [[Spiritualist Association of Great Britain]] until then. The students who came from all over the world such as Japan or certain [[African countries]] included [[Spanish citizenship|Spanish]] actress Luz Altamira or Sir [[Mark Rylance]]. The school lasted for thirty years. In the 1990s both of them gave training in [[Voice acting|voice]] and [[gesture]] to the professional company of the [[Shakespeare's Globe]]. Peter also gave courses in both the United States and throughout Europe during the same period.\n\n== La Cris\u00e1lida ==\nBridgmont supported the '''La Cris\u00e1lida Studio''', the first school focused on the 'Art of [[Speech]]' in [[Spain]], founded by his pupils speech artist '''Luz Altamira''' and [[Goya Awards]]-nominated thespian '''\u00c1lvaro Ramos''' as well as actress and author '''Pilar Altamira''' member of the '[[Anthroposophical Society]] of [[Spain]]'. This place also hosted seminars and conferences that Peter Bridgmont regularly offered between 1997 and 2003.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://goetheanum.co/fr/nouvelles/peter-bridgmont|title=Goetheanum {{!}} Peter Bridgmont, in memoriam|last=team|first=Maxime Le Roux, Nathan Querido, Das Goetheanum Wochenschrift|website=Goetheanum|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@portialeigh1/dynamic-spanish-actor-alvaro-ramos-makes-his-mark-across-several-mediums-c2392a7d74d1|title=Dynamic Spanish Actor Alvaro Ramos Makes his Mark Across Several Mediums|last=Leigh|first=Portia|date=2018-01-27|website=Medium|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n== Non-exhaustive bibliography ==\n* ''The Spear Thrower (javelin thrower), a Textbook of Ideas and Exercises for the Actor'' (1983) by Peter Bridgmont ([[ASIN]]: B000O8RJIY)<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Spear Thrower, a Textbook of Ideas and Exercises for the Actor|last=Bridgmont|first=Peter|publisher=An Grianan|year=1983|isbn=|location=London|pages=}}</ref>\n* ''The Liberation of The Actor'' (1992) by Peter Bridgmont ({{ISBN|978-0904693331}}).<ref>{{Cite book|title=Liberation of the Actor|last=Bridgmont|first=Peter|publisher=Temple Lodge Publishing|year=1992|isbn=978-0904693331|location=London|pages=}}</ref>\n\n== Quotes ==\n* English actor, theatre director and playwright [[Mark Rylance|Sir David Mark Rylance Waters]] (born 18 January 1960) who long collaborated with Bridgmont declared:\n<blockquote>''\"Peter and Barbara Bridgmont made a profound difference to my persona as an actor with their teaching about voice and speech. I use the word 'persona' carefully, as they taught me how to move with sound, through sound, persona. In our visual-material age, sound is the great undiscovered or forgotten land for actors and audiences. Reason and Emotion are all very well in speech, much needed, but with Peter and Barbara I learnt of the limbs of speech, the feet, the legs, the arms, the great will and beautiful spirit to move with speech. Just as a marvellous javelin thrower wills his spear down the pitch to the winning distance and harnesses every muscle necessary in perfect balance to achieve his aim, so, when appropriate, we speak in space and silence. It was a lucky day for me when I met them; they know some great secrets and forgotten pathways.\"''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.liberationofacting.com/|title=FOREWORD by Mark Rylance|last=Rylance|first=Mark|date=27 August 2015|website=Liberation of Acting|access-date=11 August 2018}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n* ''\"Readers who are interested in the Art of Drama may also wish to refer to The Liberation of The Actor (1992) by Peter Bridgmont\"''<ref>{{Cite book|title=Rhythms of Learning: What Waldorf Education Offers Children, Parents & Teachers|last=Steiner|first=Rudolf|publisher=SteinerBooks|year=1998|isbn=9780880104517|location=London|pages=}}</ref>\n\n== British Film Institute Archives ==\nA r\u00e9pertoire of Bridgmont's voice work for the year 1966 is available at the [[British Film Institute]] archives as follows:\n* 1966: ''The Sword Must Be Kept Sharp'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]].\n* 1966: ''What Did Greece Matter?'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]] and [[Felix Felton]].\n* 1966: ''It Will Proceed to the End'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]] and [[Felix Felton]].\n* 1966: ''One Perplexity after Another'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]] and [[Felix Felton]].\n* 1966: ''We Are on the Edge of a Precipice'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]] and [[Anton Diffring]].\n* 1966: ''Not a Penny off the Pay'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]] and [[David Bauer (actor)|David Bauer]].\n* 1966: ''It Has Advanced the Footlights'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]] and [[Anton Diffring]].\n* 1966: ''Your Death Knell Has Sounded'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]] and [[Anton Diffring]].\n* 1966: ''War Is Re-enthroned'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]] and [[Anton Diffring]].\n* 1966: ''We Neither Govern Not Misgovern'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]] and [[David Bauer (actor)|David Bauer]].\n* 1966: ''The Popular Masses Are Dull'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]] and [[Anton Diffring]].\n* 1966: ''Germany Is Reawakening'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]] and [[Anton Diffring]].\n* 1966: ''There Lies a Sleeping Giant'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]] and [[Anton Diffring]].\n* 1966: ''Who Can Conquer the Street...'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]] and [[Felix Felton]].\n* 1966: ''On the Idle Hill of Summer'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]] and [[Felix Felton]].\n* 1966: ''Make Room for Peace'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]] and [[Felix Felton]].\n* 1966: ''There Is a Great Tide Turning'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]] and [[Anton Diffring]].\n* 1966: ''This Is Such a Time'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]] and [[David Bauer (actor)|David Bauer]].\n* 1966: ''Boys You Have Been Betrayed'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]] and [[Felix Felton]].\n* 1966: ''Now I Can Die'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]] and [[David Bauer (actor)|David Bauer]].\n* 1966: ''Long Live the War'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]] and [[Felix Felton]].\n* 1966: ''What Hand Would Not Wither'' also featuring [[Michael Redgrave]], Robert Ayres and [[David Bauer (actor)|David Bauer]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2bc891e6a8|title=Voice work 1966 Bridgmont|date=1 January 2017|website=British Film Institute (BFI)|access-date=11 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Honours ==\n* The documentary on Peter and Barbara directed by [[Spanish citizenship|Spanish]] actor and director \u00c1lvaro Ramos which was eponymously titled '''The Chrysalis''' (2009) won the Best Documentary award at the High Desert International Film Festival in [[Nevada]], United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://clandestinodeactores.com/alvaro-ramos|title=Alvaro's work|date=5 May 2015|website=Clandestino de Actores|access-date=17 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nPeter's son, Andrew Bridgmont, is also an accomplished actor himself who notably starred in [[Matthew Vaughn]]'s ''[[Kingsman: The Secret Service]]'' (2014), [[James Marsh (director)|James Marsh]]'s ''[[The Theory of Everything (2014 film)|The Theory of Everything]]'' (2014) or ''[[Penny Dreadful (TV series)|Penny Dreadful]]'' (2014\u20132016).\n\n== External links ==\n* Bridgmont's [http://www.liberationofacting.com/ official website].\n\n== Sources ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bridgmont, Peter}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:English male dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male Shakespearean actors]]\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:English theatre directors]]\n[[Category:Royal Shakespeare Company members]]\n[[Category:Guildhall School of Music and Drama]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "\u62d3\u8dcb\u6c0f \u99ac", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peter_Bridgmont"}
{"title_page": "Carter Barron", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| image         = File:BARRON, CARTER. PORTRAIT LCCN2016870789.jpg\n| alt           = Carter Barron\n|birth_date={{Birth date|1905|1|30}}\n|birth_place=[[Clarkesville, Georgia]]\n|death_date={{Death date and age|mf=y|1950|11|16|1905|1|30}}\n|death_place=[[Washington, D. C.]]\n|occupation=Motion picture executive\n| module         = {{Infobox college football player|embed=yes\n|name=Carter Barron\n|school=Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets|class=Graduate\n|pastschools=[[Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets football|Georgia Tech]] (1924&ndash;1926)\n|currentposition=[[Halfback (American football)|Halfback]]\n|highlights=\n*[[College Football All-Southern Team|All-Southern]] ([[1926 College Football All-Southern Team|1926]])\n}}\n}}\n'''Carter Tate Barron''' (January 30, 1905 &ndash; November 16, 1950) was a [[college football]] player and motion picture executive.\n\n==College football==\nCarter Barron was one of a trio of football playing brothers for [[William Alexander (coach)|Bill Alexander]]'s [[Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets football]] teams, younger than [[Red Barron]] and older than Pat Barron.<ref name=alum/><ref>{{cite url|url=http://socialarchive.iath.virginia.edu/ark:/99166/w6k07cc7|title=Barron, Carter T., 1905-1950}}</ref>  Carter was selected an [[College Football All-Southern Team|All-Southern]] [[Halfback (American football)|halfback]] in 1926.<ref>{{cite news|title=Alabama Places 4 Men On Newspaper All-Southern Team|newspaper=The Kingsport Times|date=November 28, 1926}}</ref> A knee injury ultimately ended his football career.<ref name=amphi/> Carter also played on the [[baseball]], [[basketball]], and [[lacrosse]] teams.<ref name=alum>{{cite journal|url=http://issuu.com/gtalumni/docs/1950_29_2/5|title=Nationally Mourned Death Of Carter Barron, Distinguished Alumnus, Recent Georgia Tech Homecoming Reunion|journal=Georgia Tech Alumni Magazine|volume=29|number=2|date=1950}}</ref>\n\n==Motion picture executive==\n[[File:Photograph of First Archivist of the United States R. D. W. Connor Receiving Film \"Gone With The Wind\" from Senator George of Georgia and Loew's Eastern Division Manager Carter Barron, 1941.tif|thumb|Barron handling ''[[Gone with the Wind (film)|Gone With the Wind]].]]\nIn 1942, he was named [[Washington, D. C.|Washington]] representative of [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] studios.<ref name=alum/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=x1BYWGP93xAC&pg=PA184|title=Selling Air Power: Military Aviation and American Popular Culture After World War II|first=Steve|last=Call|date=1 March 2009|publisher=Texas A&M University Press|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==Amphitheatre==\nThe [[Carter Barron Amphitheatre]] is located in [[Rock Creek Park]] of [[Washington, D. C.]] The plan was expanded upon by Barron as Vice-Chairman for the Sesquicentennial Commission in 1947 as a way to memorialize the 150th Anniversary of Washington, D. C. as the nation's capital.<ref name=amphi>{{cite url|url=http://www.nps.gov/rocr/planyourvisit/cbhistory.htm|title=Carter Barron History}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPolitically a [[Democratic Party of the United States|Democrat]], Barron was a personal friend of president [[Harry Truman]],<ref name=alum/> and [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nndb.com/people/556/000055391/|title=Carter T. Barron|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nTwo of Carter Barron's nieces, Jo Barron Atchison and Alae Risse Lietch, began attending Georgia Tech games when they were young in the 1930s because of tickets sent by Carter Barron. Atchison and Lietch in 2017, were featured in an [https://www.ajc.com/sports/college/georgia-tech-104-year-old-fan-saturday-game/2Hl0cYtQk0B6G5JcmiJCCN/ article] in the ''Atlanta Journal Constitution'' about their long standing attendance to Tech Football games started by Carter Barron.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ajc.com/sports/college/georgia-tech-104-year-old-fan-saturday-game/2Hl0cYtQk0B6G5JcmiJCCN/|title=Georgia Tech\u2019s 104-year-old fan to be at Saturday\u2019s game|last=Sugiura|first=Ken|website=ajc|language=English|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[1926 College Football All-Southern Team]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barron, Carter}}\n[[Category:1905 births]]\n[[Category:1950 deaths]]\n[[Category:American football halfbacks]]\n[[Category:All-Southern college football players]]\n[[Category:People from Clarkesville, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets football players]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets baseball players]]\n[[Category:Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Washington, D.C. Democrats]]\n[[Category:People from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| image         = File:BARRON, CARTER. PORTRAIT LCCN2016870789.jpg\n| alt           = Carter Barron\n|birth_date={{Birth date|1905|1|30}}\n|birth_place=[[Clarkesville, Georgia]]\n|death_date={{Death date and age|mf=y|1950|11|16|1905|1|30}}\n|death_place=[[Washington, D. C.]]\n|occupation=Motion picture executive\n| module         = {{Infobox college football player|embed=yes\n|name=Carter Barron\n|school=Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets|class=Graduate\n|pastschools=[[Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets football|Georgia Tech]] (1924&ndash;1926)\n|currentposition=[[Halfback (American football)|Halfback]]\n|highlights=\n*[[College Football All-Southern Team|All-Southern]] ([[1926 College Football All-Southern Team|1926]])\n}}\n}}\n'''Carter Tate Barron''' (January 30, 1905 &ndash; November 16, 1950) was a [[college football]] player and motion picture executive.\n\n==College football==\nCarter Barron was one of a trio of football playing brothers for [[William Alexander (coach)|Bill Alexander]]'s [[Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets football]] teams, younger than [[Red Barron]] and older than Pat Barron.<ref name=alum/><ref>{{cite url|url=http://socialarchive.iath.virginia.edu/ark:/99166/w6k07cc7|title=Barron, Carter T., 1905-1950}}</ref>  Carter was selected an [[College Football All-Southern Team|All-Southern]] [[Halfback (American football)|halfback]] in 1926.<ref>{{cite news|title=Alabama Places 4 Men On Newspaper All-Southern Team|newspaper=The Kingsport Times|date=November 28, 1926}}</ref> A knee injury ultimately ended his football career.<ref name=amphi/> Carter also played on the [[baseball]], [[basketball]], and [[lacrosse]] teams.<ref name=alum>{{cite journal|url=http://issuu.com/gtalumni/docs/1950_29_2/5|title=Nationally Mourned Death Of Carter Barron, Distinguished Alumnus, Recent Georgia Tech Homecoming Reunion|journal=Georgia Tech Alumni Magazine|volume=29|number=2|date=1950}}</ref>\n\n==Motion picture executive==\n[[File:Photograph of First Archivist of the United States R. D. W. Connor Receiving Film \"Gone With The Wind\" from Senator George of Georgia and Loew's Eastern Division Manager Carter Barron, 1941.tif|thumb|Barron handling ''[[Gone with the Wind (film)|Gone With the Wind]].]]\nIn 1942, he was named [[Washington, D. C.|Washington]] representative of [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] studios.<ref name=alum/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=x1BYWGP93xAC&pg=PA184|title=Selling Air Power: Military Aviation and American Popular Culture After World War II|first=Steve|last=Call|date=1 March 2009|publisher=Texas A&M University Press|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==Amphitheatre==\nThe [[Carter Barron Amphitheatre]] is located in [[Rock Creek Park]] of [[Washington, D. C.]] The plan was expanded upon by Barron as Vice-Chairman for the Sesquicentennial Commission in 1947 as a way to memorialize the 150th Anniversary of Washington, D. C. as the nation's capital.<ref name=amphi>{{cite url|url=http://www.nps.gov/rocr/planyourvisit/cbhistory.htm|title=Carter Barron History}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPolitically a [[Democratic Party of the United States|Democrat]], Barron was a personal friend of president [[Harry Truman]],<ref name=alum/> and [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nndb.com/people/556/000055391/|title=Carter T. Barron|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nTwo of Carter Barron's nieces, Jo Barron Atchison and Alae Risse Lietch, began attending Georgia Tech games when they were young in the 1930s because of tickets Carter Barron would send them. In 2017, Atchison and Lietch were featured in an [https://www.ajc.com/sports/college/georgia-tech-104-year-old-fan-saturday-game/2Hl0cYtQk0B6G5JcmiJCCN/ article] in the ''Atlanta Journal Constitution'' about their long standing attendance to Tech Football games started by Carter Barron.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ajc.com/sports/college/georgia-tech-104-year-old-fan-saturday-game/2Hl0cYtQk0B6G5JcmiJCCN/|title=Georgia Tech\u2019s 104-year-old fan to be at Saturday\u2019s game|last=Sugiura|first=Ken|website=ajc|language=English|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[1926 College Football All-Southern Team]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barron, Carter}}\n[[Category:1905 births]]\n[[Category:1950 deaths]]\n[[Category:American football halfbacks]]\n[[Category:All-Southern college football players]]\n[[Category:People from Clarkesville, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets football players]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets baseball players]]\n[[Category:Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Washington, D.C. Democrats]]\n[[Category:People from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n", "name_user": "Carterbarrona", "label": "safe", "comment": "Corrected wording", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carter_Barron"}
{"title_page": "Bull Dempsey", "text_new": "{{short description|American professional wrestler|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n|name        = Bull Dempsey\n|image       = 2015-03-27 22-36-08 ILCE-6000 3269 DxO.jpg\n|image_size  = \n|caption     = Dempsey in March 2015\n|birthname   = \n|names       = Baby Hughie<ref name=\"IWD bio\"/><br />Bull Dempsey<ref name=\"WWEBio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/bulldempsey|title=Bull Dempsey|publisher=[[WWE]]|year=2013|accessdate=January 25, 2014}}</ref><br>'''Bull James'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2016/03/09/22611797.html|title=Bull Dempsey on the hunt for what's next|work=Slam! Sports|accessdate=June 9, 2016}}</ref><br />Donnie Johnson<ref name=\"Cage\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=2&nr=7631&page=4|title=Bull Dempsey profile|publisher=Cagematch|accessdate=August 31, 2014}}</ref><br />Hugh Smith<ref name=\"WrestlingData\"/><br />Masked Superstar<ref name=\"WrestlingData\"/><br />Smith James\n|height      = {{height|ft=6|in=3}}<ref name=\"WWEBio\"/>\n|weight      = {{convert|320|lb|kg|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"WWEBio\"/>\n|birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1988|01|16|mf=y}}<ref name=\"IWD bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.profightdb.com/wrestlers/bull-dempsey-9701.html|title=Bull Dempsey: Profile & Match Listing|website=profightdb}}</ref>\n|birth_place = [[Greenpoint, Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States]]<ref name=\"IWD bio\"/>\n|resides     = \n|billed      = [[Brooklyn]], New York<ref name=\"WWEBio\"/>\n|trainer     = [[Matt Osborne|Matt Borne]]<ref name=\"Cage\"/><br />[[Tazz]]<ref name=\"WrestlingData\">{{cite web|url=http://wrestlingdata.com/index.php?befehl=bios&wrestler=13325|title=WrestlingData profile|accessdate=August 31, 2014|publisher=WrestlingData}}</ref><br>[[WWE Performance Center]]<ref name=\"WrestlingData\"/>\n|debut       = October 28, 2005\n|retired     = \n}}\n'''James Smith''' (born January 16, 1988)<ref name=\"IWD bio\"/> is an American [[professional wrestler]] currently performing internationally under the ring name '''Bull James'''. He is best known for his time in  [[WWE]], where he performed on  [[NXT (WWE brand)|NXT]], under the ring name '''Bull Dempsey'''.\n\n==Professional wrestling career==\n\n===Early career (2005\u20132013)===\nSmith made his debut on October 28, 2005, at East Coast Professional Wrestling  event under the [[ring name]] Donnie \"The Body\" Johnson, where he lost to Ace Wylde. Over the next five months, Smith wrestled in [[National Wrestling Alliance]] as Baby Hughie. On September 26, 2009, at NWA New Jersey The Dennis Coralluzzo Invitational 2009, [[The Powers of Pain]] ([[The Barbarian (wrestler)|The Barbarian]] and [[The Warlord (wrestler)|The Warlord]]) defeated The Varsity Club (Baby Hughie and [[Robbie E|Rob Eckos]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=40726|title=NWA New Jersey The Dennis Coralluzzo Invitational 2009|author=Philip Kreikenbohm|publisher=Cagematch.net|accessdate=19 November 2014}}</ref> In 2010, Smith changed his ring name to Smith James. On July 21, 2011, James defeated Memphis Mofo in a TNA dark match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwinsider.com/article/60053/tna-impact-wrestling-spoilers-for-tonight.html?p=1|title=TNA IMPACT WRESTLING SPOILERS FOR TONIGHT - PWInsider.com|publisher=Pwinsider.com|accessdate=19 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, James joined The New Age Wrecking Crew with Bill Carr, Stockade and Vince Steele.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=29&nr=1357&name=The+New+Age+Wrecking+Crew|title=New Age Wrecking Crew|author=Philip Kreikenbohm|publisher=Cagematch.net|accessdate=19 November 2014}}</ref> On March 10, 2012, Steele and James entered in a tournament to crown a new ACE Tag team Champions, but were defeated in the finals by The Movement. On March 9, 2013, James and Vince Steele won the American Championship Entertainment (ACE) Tag Team Championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=92898|title=ACE Destined For Greatness|author=Philip Kreikenbohm|publisher=Cagematch.net|accessdate=19 November 2014}}</ref> They lost the titles on May 11, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=95826|title=ACE Aftermath|author=Philip Kreikenbohm|publisher=Cagematch.net|accessdate=19 November 2014}}</ref> On February 23, 2013, James and Bill Carr won the NYWC Tag Team Championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=90458|title=NYWC Psycho Circus XI|author=Philip Kreikenbohm|publisher=Cagematch.net|accessdate=19 November 2014}}</ref> However, they lost the title against [[Mikey Whipwreck]] and Stockade on June 23, 2013, his last match in the company.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=96977|title=NYWC Going The Distance|author=Philip Kreikenbohm|publisher=Cagematch.net|accessdate=19 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n===WWE (2013\u20132016)===\n\n====NXT (2013\u20132016)====\nIn June 2013, James signed a contract with [[WWE]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwinsider.com/article/77402/wwe-signing-taz-protege-and-more.html?p=1|title=WWE SIGNING TAZ PROTEGE AND MORE|publisher=Pwinsider.com|accessdate=19 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwinsider.com/article/78331/pwinsidertv-new-wwe-talents-smith-james-dan-eckos-receive-farewell-sendoff-from-nywc.html?p=1|title=PWINSIDERTV: NEW WWE TALENTS SMITH JAMES & DAN ECKOS RECEIVE FAREWELL SENDOFF FROM NYWC - PWInsider.com|publisher=Pwinsider.com|accessdate=19 November 2014}}</ref> He was assigned to the [[WWE Performance Center]]. On August 28, 2013, his name was changed to Bull Dempsey.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwinsider.com/article/79893/lots-of-new-wwe-nxt-names-revealed.html?p=1|title=LOTS OF NEW WWE NXT NAMES REVEALED|publisher=Pwinsider.com|accessdate=19 November 2014}}</ref> Dempsey made his debut in ''[[WWE NXT (TV series)|NXT]]'' on September 12, 2013, where he was defeated by [[Aiden English]]. Throughout late 2013, he made sporadic appearances as an [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#J|enhancement talent]]. In the late spring to summer, Dempsey returned to ''NXT'' as a [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#T|tweener]], [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#S|squashing]] various low carders and local talents. In August, Dempsey and [[Mojo Rawley]] formed an uneasy tag team and participated in the [[NXT Tag Team Championship]] tournament, where they were defeated by [[The Vaudevillains]] ([[Aiden English]] and [[Simon Gotch]]) in the first round, prompting Dempsey to attack Rawley in the aftermath and establishing himself a [[Heel (professional wrestling)|heel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-news/50342-wwe-nxt-results-8-21-14-rose-zayn-vs-cara-kalisto|title=WWE NXT Results - 8/21/14 (Rose/Zayn vs. Cara/Kalisto)|author=Jason Namako|publisher=WrestleView|accessdate=19 November 2014}}</ref> On September 11 at the [[NXT TakeOver: Fatal 4-Way]] event, Dempsey defeated Rawley in a squash with his new finisher The Diving Headbutt. On the September 25 episode of ''NXT'', Bull was victorious in the rematch.  Following that, he embarked on a rivalry with [[Baron Corbin]], another dominant wrestler who mostly squashed jobbers. The two competed to see how quickly they could defeat the \"local talent\", sometimes back-to-back. This eventually led to a match between the two on January 14, 2015, in which Dempsey's undefeated streak was broken by Corbin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wwenxt/2015-01-14/wwe-nxt-results-2015-01-14-27000494|title=WWE NXT results - Jan. 14, 2015: Sami Zayn & Adrian Neville battle in NXT Title rematch|publisher=[[WWE]]|accessdate=2015-01-14}}</ref>\n\nDempsey competed in the Andre the Giant Memorial Battle Qualification Tournament at [[WrestleMania Axxess]] [[WrestleMania 31|31]], but lost to [[Tyler Breeze]] in the first round. Soon after this, Dempsey's [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#G|gimmick]] was tweaked to that of an overweight, out of shape wrestler who eats too much, which also saw him turn [[face (professional wrestling)|face]] in the process.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-news/54797-wwe-nxt-results-6-10-15-samoa-joe-in-ring-debut|title=WWE NXT Results - 6/10/15 (Samoa Joe in-ring debut)|publisher=WrestleView|accessdate=2015-07-14}}</ref> After several vignettes aired to promote \"Bull-Fit\", Dempsey debuted his new gimmick on the August 26 episode of ''NXT'', where he defeated [[Elias Samson]].<ref name=aug26>{{cite web|last=Porter|first=Lovell|title=WWE NXT Results (8/26)- Fit Bull Dempsey Debuts, NXT Womens Fatal Four Way!|url=http://www.wrestlezone.com/news/613643-wwe-nxt-results-082615|accessdate=August 28, 2015|publisher=Wrestlezone}}</ref> On the February 24 episode of ''NXT'', he was defeated by [[Tommaso Ciampa]]. On the March 23 episode of ''NXT'', he and his supposed opponent [[Danny Burch]] both got beaten down by [[Samoa Joe]], before they even started the match, this led to a match between Dempsey and Joe on the following weeks episode. Dempsey lost in a quick squash match by disqualification because Joe kept his finisher, the Coquina Clutch, on Dempsey prompting NXT General Manager [[William Regal]] to try to stop him. Samoa Joe's insubordination would bring NXT Champion Finn B\u00e1lor to the ring to \"rescue\" Dempsey. The following week Dempsey lost to Joe in a squash match, this was Dempsey's final appearance for ''NXT''.\n\nOn February 5, 2016, Dempsey announced on the social network [[Twitter]] that he had been released from WWE.\n\n===Independent circuit (2016\u2013present)===\nJames began wrestling on the independent circuit following his release from NXT, using the name Bull James, a combination of his NXT name and his birth name. James announced that he was set to debut in [[Combat Zone Wrestling]], stating that he was coming after [[Sami Callihan]], also known as Solomon Crowe, facing him on March 1.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=txOjA3O_R7U</ref> On February 25, 2017, James won the NYWC Heavyweight Championship at Psycho Circus XV. On February 24, 2018, James lost the title to Alex Reynolds at Psycho Circus XVI only to regain it on March 31, 2018 at Aftermath. James lost the title to King Mega on June 30, 2018 at Going The Distance. On March 11, 2017, James won the SWF Cruiserweight Title at SWF Legacies Never Die, despite being in the gargantuan division. An SWF first. And very gay.\n\n=== Ring of Honor (2016) ===\nOn September 18, 2016, James made a surprise debut in [[Ring of Honor]]'s [[ROH Honor Rumble|Honor Rumble]], making it to the final four.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://411mania.com/wrestling/former-nxt-star-bull-dempsey-makes-roh-debut/|title=411MANIA {{!}} Former NXT Star Bull Dempsey Makes ROH Debut|website=Former NXT Star Bull Dempsey Makes ROH Debut|access-date=2016-10-23}}</ref> On October 21, 2016, James faced [[ROH World Championship|ROH World Champion]] [[Adam Cole]], in a losing effort.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rohwrestling.com/news/bull-james-gets-proving-ground-against-cole|title=Bull James Gets 'Proving Ground' Against Cole! {{!}} ROH Wrestling|website=www.rohwrestling.com|access-date=2016-10-23}}</ref> The following day James teamed up with [[Steve Corino|Mr. Wrestling III]] losing to [[B.J. Whitmer]] and [[Punisher Martinez]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pwponderings.com/2016/10/23/roh-102216-road-to-final-battle-lakeland-results/|title=ROH 10/22/16 Road to Final Battle Lakeland Results|last=News|date=2016-10-23|website=PWPonderings|access-date=2016-10-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161024023221/http://www.pwponderings.com/2016/10/23/roh-102216-road-to-final-battle-lakeland-results/|archive-date=2016-10-24|url-status=dead}}</ref> James was defeated by [[Silas Young]].\n\n==Championships and accomplishments==\n*'''American Championship Entertainment'''\n**ACE Tag Team Championship (1 time) \u2013 with Vince Steele\n*'''Atomic Wrestling Revolution'''\n**AWR Next Level Championship (1 time, current)\n*'''New York Wrestling Connection'''\n**NYWC Heavyweight Championship (2 time)\n**NYWC Fusion Championship (1 time)\n**NYWC Tag Team Championship (1 time) \u2013 with Bill Carr<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=5&nr=665|title=NYWC Tag Team Championship|author=Philip Kreikenbohm|publisher=Cagematch.net|accessdate=19 November 2014}}</ref>\n*'''''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'''''\n**Ranked No. 187 of the top 500 singles wrestlers in the ''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated#PWI 500|PWI 500]]'' in 2014<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.profightdb.com/pwi-500/2014.html|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated (PWI) 500 for 2014|accessdate=2 December 2014|work=[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]|publisher=Internet Wrestling Database}}</ref>\n*'''Superstars of Wrestling Federation'''\n**SWF Cruiserweight Championship (1 time)<ref>http://www.cagematch.net/?id=5&nr=3309</ref>\n\u2022Independent Wrestling Federation \n*IWF American Heavyweight Championship\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{WWE superstar|bulldempsey|Bull Dempsey}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dempsey, Bull}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:American male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestlers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:People from Greenpoint, Brooklyn]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American professional wrestler|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n|name        = Bull Dempsey\n|image       = 2015-03-27 22-36-08 ILCE-6000 3269 DxO.jpg\n|image_size  = \n|caption     = Dempsey in March 2015\n|birthname   = \n|names       = Baby Hughie<ref name=\"IWD bio\"/><br />Bull Dempsey<ref name=\"WWEBio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/bulldempsey|title=Bull Dempsey|publisher=[[WWE]]|year=2013|accessdate=January 25, 2014}}</ref><br>'''Bull James'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2016/03/09/22611797.html|title=Bull Dempsey on the hunt for what's next|work=Slam! Sports|accessdate=June 9, 2016}}</ref><br />Donnie Johnson<ref name=\"Cage\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=2&nr=7631&page=4|title=Bull Dempsey profile|publisher=Cagematch|accessdate=August 31, 2014}}</ref><br />Hugh Smith<ref name=\"WrestlingData\"/><br />Masked Superstar<ref name=\"WrestlingData\"/><br />Smith James\n|height      = {{height|ft=6|in=3}}<ref name=\"WWEBio\"/>\n|weight      = {{convert|320|lb|kg|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"WWEBio\"/>\n|birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1988|01|16|mf=y}}<ref name=\"IWD bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.profightdb.com/wrestlers/bull-dempsey-9701.html|title=Bull Dempsey: Profile & Match Listing|website=profightdb}}</ref>\n|birth_place = [[Greenpoint, Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States]]<ref name=\"IWD bio\"/>\n|resides     = \n|billed      = [[Brooklyn]], New York<ref name=\"WWEBio\"/>\n|trainer     = [[Matt Osborne|Matt Borne]]<ref name=\"Cage\"/><br />[[Tazz]]<ref name=\"WrestlingData\">{{cite web|url=http://wrestlingdata.com/index.php?befehl=bios&wrestler=13325|title=WrestlingData profile|accessdate=August 31, 2014|publisher=WrestlingData}}</ref><br>[[WWE Performance Center]]<ref name=\"WrestlingData\"/>\n|debut       = October 28, 2005\n|retired     = \n}}\n'''James Smith''' (born January 16, 1988)<ref name=\"IWD bio\"/> is an American [[professional wrestler]] currently performing internationally under the ring name '''Bull James'''. He is best known for his time in  [[WWE]], where he performed on  [[NXT (WWE brand)|NXT]], under the ring name '''Bull Dempsey'''.\n\n==Professional wrestling career==\n\n===Early career (2005\u20132013)===\nSmith made his debut on October 28, 2005, at East Coast Professional Wrestling  event under the [[ring name]] Donnie \"The Body\" Johnson, where he lost to Ace Wylde. Over the next five months, Smith wrestled in [[National Wrestling Alliance]] as Baby Hughie. On September 26, 2009, at NWA New Jersey The Dennis Coralluzzo Invitational 2009, [[The Powers of Pain]] ([[The Barbarian (wrestler)|The Barbarian]] and [[The Warlord (wrestler)|The Warlord]]) defeated The Varsity Club (Baby Hughie and [[Robbie E|Rob Eckos]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=40726|title=NWA New Jersey The Dennis Coralluzzo Invitational 2009|author=Philip Kreikenbohm|publisher=Cagematch.net|accessdate=19 November 2014}}</ref> In 2010, Smith changed his ring name to Smith James. On July 21, 2011, James defeated Memphis Mofo in a TNA dark match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwinsider.com/article/60053/tna-impact-wrestling-spoilers-for-tonight.html?p=1|title=TNA IMPACT WRESTLING SPOILERS FOR TONIGHT - PWInsider.com|publisher=Pwinsider.com|accessdate=19 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, James joined The New Age Wrecking Crew with Bill Carr, Stockade and Vince Steele.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=29&nr=1357&name=The+New+Age+Wrecking+Crew|title=New Age Wrecking Crew|author=Philip Kreikenbohm|publisher=Cagematch.net|accessdate=19 November 2014}}</ref> On March 10, 2012, Steele and James entered in a tournament to crown a new ACE Tag team Champions, but were defeated in the finals by The Movement. On March 9, 2013, James and Vince Steele won the American Championship Entertainment (ACE) Tag Team Championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=92898|title=ACE Destined For Greatness|author=Philip Kreikenbohm|publisher=Cagematch.net|accessdate=19 November 2014}}</ref> They lost the titles on May 11, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=95826|title=ACE Aftermath|author=Philip Kreikenbohm|publisher=Cagematch.net|accessdate=19 November 2014}}</ref> On February 23, 2013, James and Bill Carr won the NYWC Tag Team Championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=90458|title=NYWC Psycho Circus XI|author=Philip Kreikenbohm|publisher=Cagematch.net|accessdate=19 November 2014}}</ref> However, they lost the title against [[Mikey Whipwreck]] and Stockade on June 23, 2013, his last match in the company.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=1&nr=96977|title=NYWC Going The Distance|author=Philip Kreikenbohm|publisher=Cagematch.net|accessdate=19 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n===WWE (2013\u20132016)===\n\n====NXT (2013\u20132016)====\nIn June 2013, James signed a contract with [[WWE]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwinsider.com/article/77402/wwe-signing-taz-protege-and-more.html?p=1|title=WWE SIGNING TAZ PROTEGE AND MORE|publisher=Pwinsider.com|accessdate=19 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwinsider.com/article/78331/pwinsidertv-new-wwe-talents-smith-james-dan-eckos-receive-farewell-sendoff-from-nywc.html?p=1|title=PWINSIDERTV: NEW WWE TALENTS SMITH JAMES & DAN ECKOS RECEIVE FAREWELL SENDOFF FROM NYWC - PWInsider.com|publisher=Pwinsider.com|accessdate=19 November 2014}}</ref> He was assigned to the [[WWE Performance Center]]. On August 28, 2013, his name was changed to Bull Dempsey.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwinsider.com/article/79893/lots-of-new-wwe-nxt-names-revealed.html?p=1|title=LOTS OF NEW WWE NXT NAMES REVEALED|publisher=Pwinsider.com|accessdate=19 November 2014}}</ref> Dempsey made his debut in ''[[WWE NXT (TV series)|NXT]]'' on September 12, 2013, where he was defeated by [[Aiden English]]. Throughout late 2013, he made sporadic appearances as an [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#J|enhancement talent]]. In the late spring to summer, Dempsey returned to ''NXT'' as a [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#T|tweener]], [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#S|squashing]] various low carders and local talents. In August, Dempsey and [[Mojo Rawley]] formed an uneasy tag team and participated in the [[NXT Tag Team Championship]] tournament, where they were defeated by [[The Vaudevillains]] ([[Aiden English]] and [[Simon Gotch]]) in the first round, prompting Dempsey to attack Rawley in the aftermath and establishing himself a [[Heel (professional wrestling)|heel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-news/50342-wwe-nxt-results-8-21-14-rose-zayn-vs-cara-kalisto|title=WWE NXT Results - 8/21/14 (Rose/Zayn vs. Cara/Kalisto)|author=Jason Namako|publisher=WrestleView|accessdate=19 November 2014}}</ref> On September 11 at the [[NXT TakeOver: Fatal 4-Way]] event, Dempsey defeated Rawley in a squash with his new finisher The Diving Headbutt. On the September 25 episode of ''NXT'', Bull was victorious in the rematch.  Following that, he embarked on a rivalry with [[Baron Corbin]], another dominant wrestler who mostly squashed jobbers. The two competed to see how quickly they could defeat the \"local talent\", sometimes back-to-back. This eventually led to a match between the two on January 14, 2015, in which Dempsey's undefeated streak was broken by Corbin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wwenxt/2015-01-14/wwe-nxt-results-2015-01-14-27000494|title=WWE NXT results - Jan. 14, 2015: Sami Zayn & Adrian Neville battle in NXT Title rematch|publisher=[[WWE]]|accessdate=2015-01-14}}</ref>\n\nDempsey competed in the Andre the Giant Memorial Battle Qualification Tournament at [[WrestleMania Axxess]] [[WrestleMania 31|31]], but lost to [[Tyler Breeze]] in the first round. Soon after this, Dempsey's [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#G|gimmick]] was tweaked to that of an overweight, out of shape wrestler who eats too much, which also saw him turn [[face (professional wrestling)|face]] in the process.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-news/54797-wwe-nxt-results-6-10-15-samoa-joe-in-ring-debut|title=WWE NXT Results - 6/10/15 (Samoa Joe in-ring debut)|publisher=WrestleView|accessdate=2015-07-14}}</ref> After several vignettes aired to promote \"Bull-Fit\", Dempsey debuted his new gimmick on the August 26 episode of ''NXT'', where he defeated [[Elias Samson]].<ref name=aug26>{{cite web|last=Porter|first=Lovell|title=WWE NXT Results (8/26)- Fit Bull Dempsey Debuts, NXT Womens Fatal Four Way!|url=http://www.wrestlezone.com/news/613643-wwe-nxt-results-082615|accessdate=August 28, 2015|publisher=Wrestlezone}}</ref> On the February 24 episode of ''NXT'', he was defeated by [[Tommaso Ciampa]]. On the March 23 episode of ''NXT'', he and his supposed opponent [[Danny Burch]] both got beaten down by [[Samoa Joe]], before they even started the match, this led to a match between Dempsey and Joe on the following weeks episode. Dempsey lost in a quick squash match by disqualification because Joe kept his finisher, the Coquina Clutch, on Dempsey prompting NXT General Manager [[William Regal]] to try to stop him. Samoa Joe's insubordination would bring NXT Champion Finn B\u00e1lor to the ring to \"rescue\" Dempsey. The following week Dempsey lost to Joe in a squash match, this was Dempsey's final appearance for ''NXT''.\n\nOn February 5, 2016, Dempsey announced on the social network [[Twitter]] that he had been released from WWE.\n\n===Independent circuit (2016\u2013present)===\nJames began wrestling on the independent circuit following his release from NXT, using the name Bull James, a combination of his NXT name and his birth name. James announced that he was set to debut in [[Combat Zone Wrestling]], stating that he was coming after [[Sami Callihan]], also known as Solomon Crowe, facing him on March 1.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=txOjA3O_R7U</ref> On February 25, 2017, James won the NYWC Heavyweight Championship at Psycho Circus XV. On February 24, 2018, James lost the title to Alex Reynolds at Psycho Circus XVI only to regain it on March 31, 2018 at Aftermath. James lost the title to King Mega on June 30, 2018 at Going The Distance. On March 11, 2017, James won the SWF Cruiserweight Title at SWF Legacies Never Die, despite being in the gargantuan division. An SWF first.\n\n=== Ring of Honor (2016) ===\nOn September 18, 2016, James made a surprise debut in [[Ring of Honor]]'s [[ROH Honor Rumble|Honor Rumble]], making it to the final four.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://411mania.com/wrestling/former-nxt-star-bull-dempsey-makes-roh-debut/|title=411MANIA {{!}} Former NXT Star Bull Dempsey Makes ROH Debut|website=Former NXT Star Bull Dempsey Makes ROH Debut|access-date=2016-10-23}}</ref> On October 21, 2016, James faced [[ROH World Championship|ROH World Champion]] [[Adam Cole]], in a losing effort.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rohwrestling.com/news/bull-james-gets-proving-ground-against-cole|title=Bull James Gets 'Proving Ground' Against Cole! {{!}} ROH Wrestling|website=www.rohwrestling.com|access-date=2016-10-23}}</ref> The following day James teamed up with [[Steve Corino|Mr. Wrestling III]] losing to [[B.J. Whitmer]] and [[Punisher Martinez]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pwponderings.com/2016/10/23/roh-102216-road-to-final-battle-lakeland-results/|title=ROH 10/22/16 Road to Final Battle Lakeland Results|last=News|date=2016-10-23|website=PWPonderings|access-date=2016-10-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161024023221/http://www.pwponderings.com/2016/10/23/roh-102216-road-to-final-battle-lakeland-results/|archive-date=2016-10-24|url-status=dead}}</ref> James was defeated by [[Silas Young]].\n\n==Championships and accomplishments==\n*'''American Championship Entertainment'''\n**ACE Tag Team Championship (1 time) \u2013 with Vince Steele\n*'''Atomic Wrestling Revolution'''\n**AWR Next Level Championship (1 time, current)\n*'''New York Wrestling Connection'''\n**NYWC Heavyweight Championship (2 time)\n**NYWC Fusion Championship (1 time)\n**NYWC Tag Team Championship (1 time) \u2013 with Bill Carr<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=5&nr=665|title=NYWC Tag Team Championship|author=Philip Kreikenbohm|publisher=Cagematch.net|accessdate=19 November 2014}}</ref>\n*'''''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'''''\n**Ranked No. 187 of the top 500 singles wrestlers in the ''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated#PWI 500|PWI 500]]'' in 2014<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.profightdb.com/pwi-500/2014.html|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated (PWI) 500 for 2014|accessdate=2 December 2014|work=[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]|publisher=Internet Wrestling Database}}</ref>\n*'''Superstars of Wrestling Federation'''\n**SWF Cruiserweight Championship (1 time)<ref>http://www.cagematch.net/?id=5&nr=3309</ref>\n\u2022Independent Wrestling Federation \n*IWF American Heavyweight Championship\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{WWE superstar|bulldempsey|Bull Dempsey}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dempsey, Bull}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:American male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestlers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:People from Greenpoint, Brooklyn]]\n", "name_user": "68.54.146.74", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eProfessional wrestling career)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bull_Dempsey"}
